00:52:51.420 --> 00:52:53.980
So DuckDB does support indexes,

00:52:54.420 --> 00:52:57.320
but in many cases, it's not necessarily something that you need.

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:01.060
And the reason for that is because of the workloads

00:53:01.400 --> 00:53:03.680
that it's best for, but also because of columnar databases.

00:53:04.460 --> 00:53:06.220
So when you have a columnar database,

00:53:07.140 --> 00:53:12.280
by default, it's going to create some rough indexes for you automatically.

00:53:12.770 --> 00:53:15.320
So every about 100,000 rows in DuckDB,

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:17.500
we create an index there that says,

00:53:17.860 --> 00:53:19.220
what's the minimum value in this chunk

00:53:19.920 --> 00:53:21.440
and then the maximum value in this chunk?

00:53:22.260 --> 00:53:24.220
And what we'll do is then if you run a query that says,

00:53:24.460 --> 00:53:25.860
select data from this week,

00:53:26.800 --> 00:53:30.940
we're going to check, hey, which blocks have any data from this week?

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:33.660
And we can skip 90% of your data

00:53:34.090 --> 00:53:36.900
because we know that it doesn't match that filter.

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:40.000
but that's not like an individual row index.

00:53:40.820 --> 00:53:42.820
It's an index for every 100,000 rows.

00:53:43.770 --> 00:53:45.260
And it's for the analytical queries

00:53:45.370 --> 00:53:46.360
where you're looking at trends,

00:53:46.570 --> 00:53:48.400
where you're analyzing large amounts of data,

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:51.380
it tends to be really the optimal way to go about it.

00:53:51.380 --> 00:53:53.240
And that's the way most systems do it.

00:53:54.140 --> 00:53:55.620
There is an external index you can add.

00:53:56.080 --> 00:53:59.560
It's an ART index, an adaptive radix tri index,

00:54:00.120 --> 00:54:01.540
which is a pretty cool way of doing it.

00:54:01.840 --> 00:54:03.420
It's a little different than the B tree in SQLite,

00:54:03.820 --> 00:54:06.220
but it allows for those vast point lookups

00:54:06.640 --> 00:54:07.900
where if you want to grab one row,

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:10.780
you can get a very quick mapping to that individual row.

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:15.200
It tends to be just less necessary in DuctDB to do that,

00:54:15.980 --> 00:54:17.120
but we have it if you need it.

