00:58:45.900 --> 00:58:46.120
Yeah.

00:58:46.820 --> 00:58:47.920
DPD Python, that'll get you there too.

00:58:48.140 --> 00:58:48.220
Yeah.

00:58:50.260 --> 00:58:54.300
With MotherDuck and with DuckDB, you can take that and instead of being eight hours, you

00:58:54.300 --> 00:58:56.100
can run it in, you know, 15 or 30 minutes.

00:58:57.620 --> 00:59:03.520
And just that scale of change means that, you know, it's just a far more delightful

00:59:03.860 --> 00:59:08.300
experience to do those kind of data pipelines on an analytical tool as opposed to a transaction.

00:59:08.900 --> 00:59:09.320
So that's one.

00:59:09.320 --> 00:59:11.180
The other one is business intelligence tools.

00:59:11.360 --> 00:59:13.920
In a lot of cases, those start to get really slow on a transactional database.

00:59:14.650 --> 00:59:19.080
Because if you're looking at a graph, most of the time it's a trend.

00:59:19.560 --> 00:59:22.260
And most of the time it's looking at a lot of data to plot.

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:25.640
Even if it's just plotting a few points, it's looking at a lot of data to plot it.

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:29.220
And DuckDB is really excellent for that, and MotherDuck as well.

00:59:29.660 --> 00:59:33.020
There's actually a lot of business intelligence tools where they are powered by DuckDB.

00:59:34.279 --> 00:59:36.240
So Mode was acquired by PlotSpot.

00:59:36.340 --> 00:59:37.420
They're powered by DuckDB.

00:59:38.300 --> 00:59:39.760
Hex is a data science notebook.

00:59:39.860 --> 00:59:42.220
They have DuckDB as a part of their architecture.

00:59:44.400 --> 00:59:44.940
There's a couple others.

00:59:47.980 --> 00:59:49.760
We talked about some of the data types.

00:59:50.460 --> 00:59:55.020
What about JSON or document type of things, right?

00:59:55.120 --> 00:59:56.600
Where you've got a little hierarchical data.

00:59:57.280 --> 00:59:59.520
You know, there's on one end of that spectrum,

00:59:59.590 --> 01:00:00.320
we have MongoDB.

01:00:00.560 --> 01:00:01.160
That's all it does.

01:00:01.540 --> 01:00:04.520
And the other, you've got relational databases like Postgres

01:00:04.550 --> 01:00:06.300
that say, well, this column can just be

01:00:07.840 --> 01:00:09.940
JSON arbitrary stuff.

01:00:11.860 --> 01:00:15.420
Yes. We're in that space where we absolutely believe that's how

01:00:15.620 --> 01:00:17.460
most things are, a little bit of both.

01:00:17.700 --> 01:00:20.600
There is a full JSON data type in DuckDB.

01:00:21.520 --> 01:00:25.380
You can store any arbitrary document in there and then process it with

01:00:25.660 --> 01:00:27.400
some really fast JSON processing.

01:00:28.160 --> 01:00:32.400
We can also take JSON data and automatically split it out into columns if you want to

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:34.740
unnest it so you can go back and forth there.

01:00:35.240 --> 01:00:38.540
There are also specific DuckDB nested types.

01:00:39.100 --> 01:00:42.300
If you want to enforce the typing at the column level,

01:00:42.500 --> 01:00:43.440
but you want to be nested.

01:00:43.720 --> 01:00:46.020
So you could say, I know these are going to be my keys.

01:00:46.300 --> 01:00:47.420
I know this will be my structure.

01:00:48.040 --> 01:00:49.560
You can store it all in one column

01:00:50.460 --> 01:00:52.580
and it'll be very, very quick to work with.

01:00:53.860 --> 01:00:54.700
So you kind of have both.

01:00:54.720 --> 01:00:56.380
You have the full flexibility with JSON

01:00:56.500 --> 01:00:58.400
and then you also can have nested types.

01:01:00.120 --> 01:01:01.400
Can you query into them?

01:01:01.600 --> 01:01:04.220
So if I have a JSON thing that's got like purchases

01:01:04.540 --> 01:01:06.140
and then it's got a bunch of purchase objects

01:01:06.350 --> 01:01:07.680
and then like values, can I say,

01:01:07.790 --> 01:01:09.920
give me the ones that have over $100 purchases?

01:01:11.760 --> 01:01:14.720
You can do much like Postgres and SQLite

01:01:14.840 --> 01:01:16.780
have the ability to extract pieces of JSON

01:01:17.540 --> 01:01:19.180
with the path syntax of like,

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:20.860
go to this path and pull that value out.

01:01:21.360 --> 01:01:23.160
You absolutely can do that in DuckDB as well

01:01:23.320 --> 01:01:28.280
and say, okay, navigate to the customer object

01:01:28.430 --> 01:01:29.540
and then inside the customer object,

01:01:29.630 --> 01:01:32.300
go to this object and absolutely.

01:01:33.140 --> 01:01:34.040
Yeah, super cool.

01:01:34.120 --> 01:01:38.720
So, all right, well, I think there's probably more to dive into, honestly.

01:01:41.670 --> 01:01:42.460
But we've covered it.

01:01:42.650 --> 01:01:43.620
I think we've covered it pretty well.

01:01:45.020 --> 01:01:48.720
I think Duck TV is super exciting for the possibilities that it opens up.

01:01:49.340 --> 01:01:51.980
You know, there might be a ton of people out there who haven't heard of it

01:01:52.080 --> 01:01:54.680
or really just heard of it in passing and didn't really know.

01:01:56.599 --> 01:01:59.260
This in-process stuff that you can do,

01:01:59.750 --> 01:02:02.240
it really makes it quite accessible, quite easy,

01:02:03.220 --> 01:02:04.540
lowers the bar to getting started, right?

01:02:04.660 --> 01:02:06.520
You don't have to understand connections, security,

01:02:07.080 --> 01:02:09.800
servers, daemons, all of that.

01:02:09.980 --> 01:02:12.900
So I'm excited to see where this goes.

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:14.460
It's already got a ton of traction.

01:02:15.100 --> 01:02:18.060
So final call to action, maybe tell people who

01:02:18.380 --> 01:02:21.080
are in that group, what do they do?

01:02:21.740 --> 01:02:22.380
You bet.

01:02:22.380 --> 01:02:24.900
I think, obviously, pip install.dkdb, give it a try.

01:02:25.660 --> 01:02:26.940
It's anywhere you can use it.

01:02:27.440 --> 01:02:29.960
MIT license, it really can fit anywhere

01:02:30.060 --> 01:02:30.700
that you're running Python.

01:02:32.220 --> 01:02:33.960
A whole lot of other fun things you could do on top of it.

01:02:34.100 --> 01:02:35.680
There's a new extension ecosystem.

01:02:36.160 --> 01:02:38.780
So if it doesn't exist in DuckDB, but you'd like it to,

01:02:39.220 --> 01:02:42.320
you can actually build an extension for DuckDB in a variety of languages.

01:02:43.780 --> 01:02:46.460
We can all together make DuckDB into whatever we'd like.

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:47.460
Awesome.

01:02:47.740 --> 01:02:48.100
Pretty neat.

01:02:48.600 --> 01:02:50.740
Yeah. Well, good work.

